29 legally presumed to be justified in using deadly physical
30 force in self-defense or the defense of another person
31 pursuant to this subdivision (5), if the person reasonably
32 believes that another person is doing any of the following:
33 (1)a. Using or about to use unlawful deadly physical
34 force.
35 (2)b. Using or about to use physical force against an
36 occupant of a dwelling while committing or attempting to
37 commit a burglary of such dwelling.
38 (3)c. Committing or about to commit a kidnapping in any
39 degree, assault in the first or second degree, burglary in any
40 degree, robbery in any degree, forcible rape, or forcible
41 sodomy.
42 (4)d. Using or about to use physical force against an
43 owner, employee, or other person authorized to be on business
44 property when the business is closed to the public while
45 committing or attempting to commit a crime involving death,
46 serious physical injury, robbery, kidnapping, rape, sodomy, or
47 a crime of a sexual nature involving a child under the age of
48 12 years of age.
49 (5)e. In the process of unlawfully and forcefully
50 entering, or has unlawfully and forcefully entered, a
51 dwelling, residence, business property, or occupied vehicle,
52 or federally licensed nuclear power facility, or is in the
53 process of sabotaging or attempting to sabotage a federally
54 licensed nuclear power facility, or is attempting to remove,
55 or has forcefully removed, a person against his or her will
56 from any dwelling, residence, business property, or occupied
