113 of such force, unless the force was determined to be unlawful.
114 (2) Prior to the commencement of a trial in a case in
115 which a defense is claimed under this section, the court
116 having jurisdiction over the case, upon motion of the
117 defendant, shall conduct a pretrial hearing to determine
118 whether force, including deadly force, used by the defendant
119 was justified or whether it was unlawful under this section.
120 During any pretrial hearing to determine immunity, the
121 defendant must show by a preponderance of the evidence that he
122 or she is immune from criminal prosecution.
123 (3) If, after a pretrial hearing under subdivision (2),
124 the court concludes that the defendant has proven by a
125 preponderance of the evidence that force, including deadly
126 force, was justified, the court shall enter an order finding
127 the defendant immune from criminal prosecution and dismissing
128 the criminal charges.
129 (4) If the defendant does not meet his or her burden of
130 proving immunity at the pre-trial hearing, he or she may
131 continue to pursue the defense of self-defense or defense of
132 another person at trial. Once the issue of self-defense or
133 defense of another person has been raised by the defendant,
134 the state continues to bear the burden of proving beyond a
135 reasonable doubt all of the elements of the charged conduct.
136 (e)(g) A law enforcement agency may use standard
137 procedures for investigating the use of force described in
138 subsection (a)this section, but the agency may not arrest the
139 any person for using force unless it determines that there is
140 probable cause that the force used was unlawful."
